article.description: Mwadi Mabika and the Los Angeles Sparks  appear ready to get on a major roll.
article.headline: Reserves chip in 35 for Sparks
article.linkText: Surging Sparks leave Lynx in the dust
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The "Goon Squad" gave the Los Angeles
Sparks a much-needed lift.

Mwadi Mabika scored 20 points and the Sparks got 37 points from
their reserves in an 83-67 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on
Sunday night.

"We have a good mix of veterans and young players that really
makes us a deep team," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said.
"Tonight, I think they took a big step into forming their own
identity. I call them my 'Goon Squad.' There's no doubt that our
bench is going to be the key for us to win the title."

Minnesota rookie Nicole Ohlde led the Lynx with a career-high 19
points and grabbed seven rebounds, while Teresa Edwards added 10
points.

Lisa Leslie scored 13 points and Nikki Teasley added 11 for Los
Angeles, but starting forward DeLisha Milton-Jones was held
scoreless. That didn't deter the Sparks.

Rookie Christi Thomas led the Sparks' reserves with 14 points
and a game-high eight rebounds in 23 minutes, while Tamecka Dixon
scored 11 points and Tamika Whitmore added 10 points on 4-of-5
shooting.

"We feel like we don't have a starting five -- we have 11
starters," Thomas said. "Coach tells us that he not only wants us
to match the intensity of the starters when we come in, but to
exceed it."

Minnesota forced eight turnovers in the first 10 minutes, on the
way to a 21-14 lead. Dixon and Whitmore scored the next 12 points
for Los Angeles, with Dixon's long jump shot putting the Sparks
ahead 26-24.

Katie Smith put the Lynx back ahead with a 3-pointer on the next
possession, but it was her only field goal of the game. Minnesota's
leading scorer at 17.4 points per game finished with just five
points on 1-of-3 shooting.

"I just didn't get the ball in a lot of good spots, and they
played good defense," Smith said. "But we found the open person.
I'm not one to force up a lot of shots."

Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio wasn't as quick to credit the
Sparks for shutting down Smith.

"At times, Katie removes herself from the offense and lets
other players take over," McConnell Serio said. "I thought she
was very passive offensively tonight. That's something we'll need
to talk about."

The Sparks grabbed the lead for good on a driving basket by
Teasley with 5:40 to play in the first half, then closed with an
11-3 run to take a 53-42 lead at the break.

Los Angeles appeared ready to turn the game into a blowout when
it scored the first six points of the second half to open a 59-42
lead. But the Sparks did not score over the next five minutes, and
Minnesota went on a 12-0 run to get back to within 61-57 with 9:26
to play.

Teasley ended Los Angeles' dry spell with a 3-pointer, Leslie
followed with a basket in the low post and Mabika converted a
three-point play over a span of 1:30 to put down Minnesota's rally.
